article.description: Eddie House scored 22 points, including 10 in the fourth quarter, as the Miami Heat snapped out of its recent skid and defeated Milwaukee 102-97 Friday night.
article.headline: House's season-high keeps Bucks in tailspin
article.linkText: House fires up, leads Heat past Bucks
article.story:
MIAMI (AP) -- Eddie House made sure the Milwaukee Bucks did not gain their first road win in more than a month. House scored 22 points, including 10 in the fourth quarter, as the Miami Heat snapped out of its recent skid and defeated Milwaukee 102-97 Friday night. The Heat snapped a three-game losing streak and won for only the second time in nine games. Milwaukee lost its eighth straight road game and for the 11th time in 15 games overall. House, a streaky shooter whose playing time depends largely on how much he's scoring, had his biggest output of the season. He shot 7-of-12 from the floor, including 4-of-5 from 3-point range, as Miami kept its slim playoff hopes alive. "I got some great looks and just knocked them in," House said. "The job of the guys off the bench is to give the starters a lift. Sometimes the starters don't get off to a great start, and we try to come in and give them some energy." The Bucks, now seventh in the Eastern Conference standings, haven't won on the road since beating Cleveland on March 3. "We played hard enough to win tonight," Bucks coach George Karl said. "Miami played a little better than we did. We haven't played this hard until tonight, so I'm encouraged." Alonzo Mourning added 18 points and 10 rebounds and Eddie Jones scored 17 points for Miami, which improved to 9-0 when scoring 100 or more points. "I know what we're capable of doing," Mourning said. "That's no mystery. It's a matter of us developing a level of consistency, and that's something we haven't done. We had a very critical lapse at the wrong time. "We know we can get out of this. I've said it before: The only people who believe what we're capable of doing are the guys in this room and the coaching staff. That's why we continue to work the game the way we're working it." The Heat, already assured of their first losing season since 1994-95, have seven games left -- five of them at home. "Our record indicates who we are, where we are, and the dilemma we're in," Heat coach Pat Riley said. "But, it's been a great group all year. I think they're going to keep playing it right out." Sam Cassell and Glen Robinson each scored 19 points for Milwaukee. Ray Allen scored 18 points in 23 minutes off the bench after missing the previous six games with a knee injury. "We need to get guys healthy," Cassell said. "Having Ray back in the lineup helps, but he is not 100 percent. We have a lot of guys playing hurt. We just need to rest up before the playoffs. When we're healthy, I like our chances." House helped rally the Heat in the fourth quarter. With his team trailing 78-77 at the start of the period, House hit a pair of free throws and a 3-pointer to put the Heat ahead 84-80. A 3-pointer by House stretched Miami's lead to 95-87 with 2:37 left, and the Heat had to sweat out a late run by the Bucks. Allen's free throws pulled the Bucks to 98-96 with 12 seconds left, but Brian Grant and House each hit a pair of free throws in the closing seconds to seal the win. "We need to fight for that last spot," House said. "We need to make it happen. We can't think about the past, only about the task at hand, and that's getting into the playoffs." Milwaukee led 53-48 at halftime behind 11 points apiece from Cassell and Robinson. The Bucks led by as many as 13, but the Heat closed the gap behind 12 points off the bench from House. The Heat put together a 23-11 run to open a 71-64 lead, but the Bucks answered with a 12-4 spurt to close the third period and take a 78-77 lead.

Game notes
The Bucks suspended backup guard Rafer Alston from Friday's game for missing practice Thursday. Alston is expected to rejoin the club for Sunday's game at Philadelphia. ...Milwaukee backup center Greg Foster, who has missed 56 games while on the injured list with a cervical bulging disc, was activated but didn't play. ...The Bucks are 11-18 since the All-Star break. ... The past seven games in the series have been decided by a combined 24 points. ... At 16-20, the Heat must win their final five home games to avoid a losing season at home, which hasn't happened since 90-91.
